manufacturerProductDescription.media_text: Tips: 1. 80MB/s reading and 50MB/s writing speed are got from the testing software. When using, the speeds may vary according to host device, drive capacity, file attributes, operating systems, applications or other factors. 2. 1GB = 1,000 Megabytes= 1,000,000 Kilobytes=1,000,000,000 Bytes in USB flash drive. Each storage device has a reserved memory for formatting and other functions, then the actual capacity is about 93% of the labelled capacity. 3. USB-A and Lightning plugs are not allowed to use simultaneously. 4. Due to the high-speed transmission and the metal casing, the USB thumb drive will heat up when in use, this is a normal part of the work, no worry! 5. The default file format is exFAT. In case your device doesn't recognize our USB Type-C flash drive, please try to format it with NTFS or FAT 32. However, FAT32 format can not store a single file with a capacity greater than 4GB. And NTFS are not so widely comptiable to various devices as exFAT. 6. We suggest you back up the stored data regularly, the data stored in the USB flash drive is not covered in warranties.

reviews.reviewDate: Reviewed in the United States on December 7, 2023
reviews.reviewTitle: 5.0 out of 5 stars Decent performance. Sturdy shell.
reviews.reviewText: I’ve always been skeptical of offbrand storage, but this one pleasantly surprised me. It came with a USB-C cable, as well as an adapter for a standard size USB three connection. Also included is a little case that you can put the drive in. My only gripe with the case is that there’s no place to put the cable and the drive is useless without the cable, so it kind of causes a little problem there.The drive was recognized immediately on my computer, and I ran test and confirmed that it had a true 512 gigs of storage. Performance was not quite as advertised, but it worked well enough that I didn’t feel like I was waiting unnecessarily.The indicator light on the side is helpful, but honestly becomes a little annoying if you’re writing and reading because it’s so bright. I just flipped the drive over so that it was not flashing in my face.Temperature wise the drive did heat up with prolonged use, but it didn’t get uncomfortably hot. So far I’ve used it on two separate operating systems without issue and I’ve even used it as a buildable drive and it has worked great.
